Conceptual Boundaries

Ioannicis of Ravenna

fl. AD 680s-711

Agnellus of Ravenna, Book of the Pontiffs of the Church of Ravenna, 830s and 840s

Sant'Apollinare in Classe, Ravenna

Ioannicis 'the most wise set forth all the antiphons which we sing now on the Sundays of the cross or of the holy apostles or martyrs or confessors and virgins, not only in Latin speech but also in Greek words, since he was a great orator in both tongues.' LPR p. 263

In the time [of bishop Theodore, 677-91] it happened that the notary of the exarch died, for whom the exarch grieved because he did not have a similar wise man in the palace who could compose imperial letters or complete other written charters which were necessary. When he indicated his sadness to his attendants, they said to him, "There is here a youth, one Ionannicis by name, most skilled in writing … and sprung from noblest blood." Uplifted at having heard this speech, he ordered him to come. … When [Ioannicis] stood before him, the exarch ordered a letter to be brought which had come to him from the emperor, written in Greek, and said to him, "Read it." But he frowned, and said, "Do you order, my lord, that I read it in Greek, as it is written, or with Latin words?" Then the admiring exarch, together with the leaders of the assembly of the people, ordered a charter to be brought written in Latin letters. Taking it, he read the whole thing in Greek. Then the exarch was pleased at the knowledge of this Ioannicis. LPR p. 239-40

After three years [in the exarch's service], the emperor in Constantinople ordered a letter to be written to the exarch saying thus: 'Send to me that man who produces such compositions and poems which you have sent to me.' [The exarch,] burdened by necessity as if by oaken beams, sent him to Constantinople. And when the emperor had looked at him, he did not [at first] believe in [Ioannicis'] knowledge. After a few days, [Ioannicis'] learning shone forth, and [the emperor] placed him among the leading men. … In the time [of Bishop Damian, 692-708] the said Ioannicis returned from Constantinople to Ravenna, and his wisdom was famed in all Italy. LPR p. 240, 247-8
